WEBVTT

00:01.282 --> 00:10.597
One of the reasons that we still love the Psalms three millennia later is that they are songs.

00:12.940 --> 00:16.947
This is Hebrew poetry that was written to be sung.

00:16.987 --> 00:29.106
They were written by hearts that had been moved and they captured those emotions and bottled it up in verse.

00:29.954 --> 00:44.109
so that other people might read and experience those emotions that later generations would worship our God together even 3,000 years later in Sweden.

00:46.292 --> 00:52.358
For Christians today, we have at least three ways that we should read every Psalm.

00:52.378 --> 00:57.263
These are not options, like pick an option, but we read every Psalm in these three ways.

00:58.084 --> 00:59.666
One is the original

00:59.970 --> 01:00.370
reading.

01:01.311 --> 01:08.959
The original author, this one tells us to turn David to an original audience which would have been 3,000 years ago.

01:09.019 --> 01:12.722
The second way is in relation to Jesus.

01:13.844 --> 01:22.932
The God who inspired and preserved the Psalms sent his own son at the center of history and every psalm has something to tell us about Jesus.

01:25.014 --> 01:28.658
How Jesus fulfills the psalm and amazingly

01:29.186 --> 01:34.794
how God himself as man, as Israelite, would have taken these Psalms on his lips.

01:35.996 --> 01:41.965
So you imagine Jesus speaking every Psalm in the first century.

01:42.485 --> 01:49.716
A third way then is how these Psalms relate to the church, the New Covenant church.

01:50.557 --> 01:52.139
These Psalms are for today.

01:52.400 --> 01:54.002
These Psalms are for the church.

01:54.850 --> 02:00.016
Paul says everything written in former times was written for you that you may have hope.

02:01.718 --> 02:03.700
And so the Psalms are all written for the church.

02:04.701 --> 02:12.830
And we need to have all three of these perspectives in mind this morning, but I want to focus, especially on the last one, the church.

02:14.892 --> 02:23.762
And not just the global church or the universal church, but you in particular.

02:25.058 --> 02:31.305
my dear, new Swedish friends, brothers and sisters, and Jesus.

02:34.709 --> 02:42.517
If I might be so bold, I would like to address the Swedish church this morning.

02:43.699 --> 02:44.479
Not the state church.

02:46.542 --> 02:54.130
By Swedish church, I mean faithful, Bible believing, born again, Christians.

02:55.330 --> 02:56.111
in Sweden.

02:57.673 --> 03:09.411
So our orienting question this morning as we come to Psalm 8 is, what would Psalm 8 have the true Swedish church to be?

03:10.292 --> 03:17.623
There's a vision here just as we have a vision of our worship together in the new heavens and new earth.

03:19.045 --> 03:22.450
I had that vision and hearing you sing to Jesus and Swedish.

03:23.010 --> 03:27.516
There's a vision here for what the church in Sweden should be.

03:29.459 --> 03:31.662
Psalm 8 casts a vision of the future.

03:31.702 --> 03:33.184
It doesn't only have the past part.

03:33.805 --> 03:34.967
Can I talk about some fundamentals?

03:35.547 --> 03:36.629
In the past, we'll see that.

03:36.709 --> 03:37.731
Going back to Genesis 1.

03:38.712 --> 03:47.865
And it doesn't only marvel at God's grace in the present, as we'll see, but Psalm 8 swells with a hope for a coming future.

03:48.826 --> 03:51.730
And that's not only a future for David when he wrote it,

03:52.354 --> 03:54.196
It doesn't only anticipate Jesus to come.

03:54.397 --> 03:55.759
That's a future still for us.

03:56.460 --> 04:00.425
It is a future that still lies ahead of us in 2025.

04:02.888 --> 04:16.226
Psalm 8 gives us as Christians and gives you as sweetest Christians a vision for corporate life in the church as a people who cherish the majesty of God.

04:18.970 --> 04:22.194
I love that we sing that song that started with majesty.

04:23.586 --> 04:25.369
I love that word majesty.

04:27.371 --> 04:28.793
This is what Psalm 8 is about.

04:28.994 --> 04:32.238
It celebrates the majesty of God.

04:33.700 --> 04:37.225
Majesty is an attribute of God.

04:37.626 --> 04:40.009
And sometimes we don't think of it as an attribute.

04:40.029 --> 04:44.896
We think of his, his omnipotence, his omnipresence.

04:45.918 --> 04:51.826
We think about his power, his holiness, his love, his compassion.

04:53.122 --> 05:00.550
But His Majesty, that's an attribute, a lesser known, often neglected attribute of our God.

05:00.830 --> 05:01.951
He is majestic.

05:03.333 --> 05:07.097
And this Psalm in particular celebrates His Majesty.

05:08.959 --> 05:19.730
The reason I love this attribute of Majesty, even though it's often overlooked, is because Majesty celebrates His greatness and His goodness.

05:20.418 --> 05:25.925
It brings together two things that sometimes you might leave apart, but Majesty brings him together.

05:27.848 --> 05:32.474
It brings together his strength, but also his beauty.

05:34.397 --> 05:36.259
It's not just strength, not just beauty.

05:36.560 --> 05:38.042
Majesty brings him together.

05:38.102 --> 05:41.787
He's beautifully strong, strongly beautiful.

05:43.829 --> 05:50.418
Majesty is not only a fitting term for mountains and seascapes, oceans,

05:50.530 --> 05:59.503
waterfalls, but it is a particularly fitting descriptor of the one that Isaiah calls the majestic one.

06:01.166 --> 06:07.495
Isaiah chapter 10 verse 31, 34, our God is the majestic one.

06:07.555 --> 06:17.330
Majesty, different than other attributes is an emotive or affective word.

06:19.746 --> 06:26.757
It indicates a greatness in God that the speaker of the term, the praiseer, finds wonderful.

06:28.940 --> 06:32.966
There's a bigness that the praiseer sees as beautiful.

06:34.288 --> 06:37.493
There is imposing size viewed with delight.

06:39.316 --> 06:44.404
There's imposing power that is attractive rather than scary.

06:46.867 --> 06:48.530
Majesty calls attention

06:48.610 --> 06:53.676
to the greatness of God's glory and the glory of His greatness.

06:56.440 --> 07:06.112
So when God reveals Himself at the Red Sea in the cloud of fire that turns on the Egyptians, God's enemies cry terror.

07:08.975 --> 07:15.563
And His people praise His majesty as they do in Exodus chapter 15.

07:15.864 --> 07:17.906
That's where majesty first

07:18.050 --> 07:22.515
appears in the Bible as his friends, his redeemed.

07:23.156 --> 07:27.301
Those who love him praise his majesty in rescuing them.

07:30.625 --> 07:37.353
And God's majesty in Psalm 8 is first glimpsed in the world that he made.

07:37.393 --> 07:41.738
This we might call his natural majesty.

07:41.758 --> 07:44.882
We're going to see two modes of his majesty in Psalm 8.

07:45.538 --> 07:47.981
The first is His natural majesty.

07:48.001 --> 07:49.463
That's the last part of verse 1.

07:51.245 --> 07:57.794
You have set your glory above the heavens.

07:57.814 --> 07:58.575
And that's interesting.

08:01.298 --> 08:09.148
So that is God's majesty is above the majesty of the heavens.

08:10.350 --> 08:13.714
Their majesty, which David sees, and writes down in the Psalm,

08:14.402 --> 08:23.573
And the majesty that we're to see in the heavens declares a greater majesty than the majesty of the heavens.

08:25.095 --> 08:30.541
And so David looks at those heavens in verse three, and apparently he's looking at night.

08:31.482 --> 08:33.024
There's no mention of sun here.

08:34.085 --> 08:37.509
We get a mention of moon and stars.

08:38.290 --> 08:41.394
So I envision David out at night.

08:42.050 --> 08:46.817
He must have had to get outside of Gothenburg where you can actually see stars away from city lights.

08:48.540 --> 08:59.976
And he says in verse three, when I look at your heavens, the work of your fingers, the moon and the stars, which you have said in place, pause right there.

09:02.180 --> 09:05.144
Don't miss that David looks.

09:08.529 --> 09:09.330
He observes.

09:10.850 --> 09:13.634
He stops his busy, kingly life.

09:15.317 --> 09:17.520
He takes the time to look up at night.

09:18.081 --> 09:22.267
He pauses to see glory overhead as the majesty of God.

09:25.371 --> 09:26.373
Just can't help but ask.

09:27.274 --> 09:28.356
Do you still pause?

09:28.416 --> 09:31.721
Do you ever stop and look?

09:34.084 --> 09:37.850
Let me carry these devices around with us, these distraction devices.

09:38.831 --> 09:40.754
The pixels pull us in.

09:40.962 --> 09:46.510
the busyness of 21st century life, especially city life, pulls us in.

09:46.530 --> 09:48.432
Do you stop?

09:48.492 --> 09:49.554
I want to stop.

09:51.056 --> 10:02.412
I want to have a pace of life that is like Psalm 8 where there's room for pauses to see majesty in God's world and take it up to the majesty that's above the majesty as you can see with your eyes.

10:02.452 --> 10:09.842
So David stops in his busy, kingly life.

10:10.210 --> 10:34.378
and he observes divine majesty and he unhurriedly meditates on that majesty and he feels deeply about that majesty and he crafts a poem about the majesty of God so that others, including us, might see it and feel it and express his majesty.

10:35.880 --> 10:36.901
So I want to be like this.

10:36.941 --> 10:37.842
I want to look

10:38.146 --> 10:46.995
at the wonders of the world and wonder at the God it reveals.

10:47.015 --> 10:56.264
How tragic would it be to look at the wonders of the world and be blind to the majesty of God?

10:56.324 --> 11:06.994
Any unbeliever can look at the wonders of this beautiful landscape in Sweden and see majesty and

11:07.106 --> 11:08.027
Stop right there.

11:09.209 --> 11:14.175
Not get to the majesty that's above the majesty of the heavens.

11:16.918 --> 11:22.184
I love that David says in verse 3, your heavens.

11:23.065 --> 11:23.586
Did you see that?

11:24.507 --> 11:25.508
He doesn't even say the heavens.

11:25.909 --> 11:28.572
Now look at the heavens like a scientist.

11:31.436 --> 11:36.722
When I look at God, your heavens, you made them.

11:37.378 --> 11:37.959
You own them.

11:39.121 --> 11:40.603
You're declaring your glory in them.

11:40.623 --> 11:41.804
You're showing yourself in them.

11:43.447 --> 11:48.234
When I look at your heavens, the work of your fingers.

11:48.534 --> 11:50.016
What does fingers mean?

11:50.838 --> 11:53.341
Now, fingers can mean detail.

11:54.262 --> 11:58.168
How the little stars twinkle, twinkle in a little detail.

12:01.072 --> 12:04.978
But I think what fingers means here is how easy God did it.

12:05.666 --> 12:07.208
The hand represents power.

12:07.288 --> 12:08.269
You use something with the hand.

12:08.750 --> 12:10.352
You exert your power to do something.

12:10.792 --> 12:13.275
Fingers, fingers are so much weaker.

12:14.637 --> 12:20.584
If you do a task without lifting a finger, that means you did it really easy.

12:23.227 --> 12:27.132
That's what the majesty of creation is to our God.

12:27.933 --> 12:31.858
He did it so easy with his fingers.

12:33.698 --> 12:39.184
It didn't take any heavy lifting from God to make the majesties of this world.

12:40.446 --> 12:45.472
Majestic as the great features of his creation are, he's the majestic one.

12:45.512 --> 12:48.776
Look from them to him.

12:48.796 --> 13:01.010
The majesties of mountains and oceans is as nothing compared to the majesty of the God who made them and made them with his fingers.

13:02.082 --> 13:08.170
He broke no sweat doing it.

13:08.190 --> 13:23.091
So what would our majestic God through Psalm 8 have our churches be and have faithful, Bible believing, born again, Swedish churches to be in this generation?

13:24.753 --> 13:31.122
So I have as a daring, hopefully humble American,

13:33.090 --> 13:36.375
five charges for you from Psalm 8.

13:37.677 --> 13:42.764
My dear brothers and sisters in Sweden and for your churches.

13:43.745 --> 13:47.470
Hopefully you're faithful Christ-adoring churches.

13:47.931 --> 13:52.998
Number one, be a commending people.

13:54.961 --> 13:56.924
Be a commending people.

13:58.166 --> 14:01.170
And this is from verse one and verse nine.

14:02.146 --> 14:04.971
And by commending, I just mean praising.

14:07.376 --> 14:09.500
Be a praising people.

14:10.422 --> 14:12.486
This is a psalm of praise.

14:13.488 --> 14:19.740
And the great refrain that begins and ends the psalm commends God, praises God.

14:20.482 --> 14:23.327
This whole psalm, a second person, it's addressed to God.

14:23.527 --> 14:24.850
Not all the psalms are like this.

14:25.666 --> 14:27.949
Some Psalms don't address God in second person.

14:27.969 --> 14:29.151
Some do and go back and forth.

14:29.391 --> 14:31.153
This one is just all praise to God.

14:31.434 --> 14:33.096
Second person to God the whole time.

14:34.538 --> 14:35.720
You, you, you.

14:37.182 --> 14:39.625
So look at verse one or nine.

14:39.765 --> 14:42.008
We can read verse one and nine at the same time.

14:43.891 --> 14:44.091
All right.

14:44.111 --> 14:50.079
Oh Lord, our Lord, how majestic is your name in all the earth.

14:53.564 --> 14:55.346
To praise God's name,

14:55.842 --> 14:58.346
is to praise God Himself.

14:59.728 --> 15:02.873
You cannot praise His name without praising Him.

15:04.715 --> 15:07.479
You might praise someone without knowing their name.

15:07.760 --> 15:12.086
If somebody does a random act of kindness for you on the street, you might praise how wonderful they are.

15:12.106 --> 15:14.209
I didn't even get their name, but praise that person.

15:15.952 --> 15:20.980
But when you know a person's name, you can't praise that name without praising the person.

15:23.203 --> 15:25.266
This is praise for God Himself.

15:25.346 --> 15:28.869
What name emphasizes here, why would David use name?

15:28.949 --> 15:31.512
Why not just say praise of the majesty of God?

15:32.072 --> 15:33.113
How majestic is your name?

15:33.133 --> 15:33.814
Why say name?

15:33.854 --> 15:40.660
Name emphasizes that God has revealed himself to his people.

15:41.001 --> 15:43.023
He's told us his name.

15:43.823 --> 15:44.804
He's revealed himself.

15:46.085 --> 15:50.410
He told his old covenant people his name through Moses.

15:51.771 --> 15:55.154
And he has revealed his new covenant name to his church.

15:55.426 --> 16:06.858
The name that is above every name, Jesus, and the Father of Jesus, and the Spirit of Jesus.

16:08.720 --> 16:22.034
To praise God, not just as generic God, but to praise Him by name is to receive and to cherish His self revelation of Himself to us.

16:23.202 --> 16:25.125
Oh, it's so precious that we have this book.

16:25.145 --> 16:26.106
This is no mere book.

16:26.507 --> 16:28.270
It's no mere record of what happened.

16:28.290 --> 16:34.078
This is the living speech of the living God in this book, His self-revelation to us.

16:39.406 --> 16:49.842
The God of majesty who we praise is not a God of our imagination or our speculation or our human reason or our best intuition.

16:51.266 --> 16:53.750
He is a God who has revealed Himself.

16:54.571 --> 17:02.803
He began to reveal Himself to the world through His old covenant people, and He has revealed Himself climacticly to all nations in Jesus.

17:05.627 --> 17:18.066
Last month, before I knew I was coming to Sweden, I had the opportunity to go to my former church, Bethlehem Baptist, in preach.

17:19.490 --> 17:21.452
And my assignment was Psalm 8.

17:21.472 --> 17:25.836
This is the first time I'd been back in 10 years.

17:26.337 --> 17:30.601
I'd been at Bethlehem Baptist from 2003 to 2015.

17:32.182 --> 17:36.186
And we went out as a plant of Bethlehem Baptist to plant cities church in St. Paul.

17:36.206 --> 17:42.692
So Bethlehem's in Minneapolis and the twin city is St. Paul and our church, our 10 year old church is in St. Paul.

17:45.014 --> 17:48.978
And as Joelle mentioned, Bethlehem Baptist Church.

17:49.058 --> 17:59.871
For its first 74 years of church life, from 1871 until 1945, it was first Swedish Baptist Church of Minneapolis.

18:02.874 --> 18:04.756
1945, they changed the name to Bethlehem.

18:05.437 --> 18:11.784
And there's still some Swedes around Bethlehem, including some that are on this trip as part of the prayer team.

18:14.307 --> 18:16.530
And when I preached Psalm 8,

18:17.538 --> 18:30.837
Ed Bethlehem Baptist Church last month, I had the privilege of commending them for being a praising people.

18:30.857 --> 18:32.940
They sing, they really sing.

18:32.980 --> 18:39.910
And because they sing, their little 10-year-old church plant in St. Paul sings.

18:40.972 --> 18:45.458
And so as a pastor, I love this one, my favorite conversation is a pastor.

18:45.698 --> 18:48.061
Pastors have to remember some of their favorite conversations.

18:48.481 --> 18:50.483
She helped balance out the ones that aren't her favorites.

18:51.024 --> 18:57.572
One of my favorites is, from a guest, she'll say, wow, your people really sing.

18:57.632 --> 18:59.454
They're really sing.

18:59.474 --> 19:02.437
It's like, oh good, praise the Lord, yes they sing.

19:02.457 --> 19:07.703
And I tell them, I said, we get that from our mother.

19:10.126 --> 19:13.810
First Swedish Baptist of Minneapolis taught us how to sing.

19:14.626 --> 19:16.769
We sing like we do because of our mama.

19:17.971 --> 19:19.533
You better not talk about about our mama.

19:23.499 --> 19:27.926
And this is, I mentioned earlier, this has been, I guess, a kind of surprise.

19:27.986 --> 19:29.048
I shouldn't be surprised.

19:29.749 --> 19:30.930
A kind of surprise.

19:32.272 --> 19:36.218
The singing that I've gotten to experience here this weekend.

19:36.739 --> 19:41.426
You are a people who sing to our majestic God.

19:42.242 --> 19:49.172
And so Salmate, the first thing Salmate would say to you, Swedish church, is a bound still more.

19:51.135 --> 19:52.317
You're doing well.

19:53.799 --> 19:55.542
Keep singing like you sing.

19:55.843 --> 19:58.567
Don't lose that penchant for praise.

19:59.308 --> 20:00.169
Lean into it.

20:01.832 --> 20:08.722
Keep loosing reserved Swedish tongues in praise of our God.

20:12.290 --> 20:17.197
I think that will be the thing I remember most from this weekend as you're praising Jesus.

20:18.578 --> 20:19.660
And here's an amazing thing.

20:21.082 --> 20:33.518
When God looses the tongues of Christians to praise Him, He teaches us how our tongues might be loosed to commend each other, to praise each other.

20:35.241 --> 20:42.290
Being a praising people on Sunday morning begins to overflow into being a praising people throughout the week.

20:43.522 --> 20:49.430
When we learn to praise our God, we find ourselves more ready to praise and to encourage each other.

20:49.450 --> 20:52.214
And you know what?

20:52.234 --> 20:57.782
Our God is not at all threatened when His children praise each other.

20:59.124 --> 20:59.865
He loves it.

21:01.567 --> 21:12.562
He delights when His children praise Him, and He smiles with joy when His children see evidences of grace in the lives of other children, and they say it.

21:12.866 --> 21:14.729
They praise it, they commend it.

21:18.293 --> 21:19.976
So be a commending people.

21:21.017 --> 21:30.951
Keep commending our God as you do and be a commending people of each other with your wonderfully loosed Swedish tongues.

21:32.032 --> 21:33.554
Number two, be a called people.

21:35.036 --> 21:38.701
This is verses six to eight, a called people.

21:39.963 --> 21:42.226
And by called here, I don't have in mind

21:42.914 --> 21:47.360
Conversion, though, I guess, in Sweden.

21:48.161 --> 21:49.583
Yeah, be that, be converted.

21:51.645 --> 21:53.147
Be a converted church, amen.

21:54.829 --> 22:03.861
But I have in mind here the call of vocation, of your calling in life, your specific calling, callings in life.

22:04.802 --> 22:06.024
Look at verses six to eight again.

22:07.526 --> 22:10.770
You have given man dominion over the works of your hands.

22:11.554 --> 22:18.462
You have put all things under his feet, all sheep and oxen and also the beasts of the field, the birds of the heavens and the fish of the sea.

22:18.502 --> 22:25.249
Now, as you hear verses 6 and 8 there, what does that sound like?

22:25.269 --> 22:26.290
Does it bring anything to mind?

22:27.431 --> 22:30.995
Beasts, birds, fish, that little triad, beasts, birds and fish.

22:31.596 --> 22:32.997
Any other passage come to mind?

22:35.961 --> 22:38.263
He's hearkening back to Genesis 1.

22:39.525 --> 22:40.786
So Genesis 1,

22:41.282 --> 23:01.513
Chapter 1, verse 28 says this, be fruitful and multiply and fill the earth and subdue it and have dominion, there's that same language, that's where it's coming from in Psalm 8, have dominion over the fish of the sea and over the birds of the heavens and over every living thing that moves on the earth.

23:04.177 --> 23:10.226
The first sense of call in Psalm 8 is to the original commission that God gave

23:10.306 --> 23:11.928
humanity at creation.

23:14.210 --> 23:16.653
Sometimes we call this the cultural mandate.

23:18.535 --> 23:32.731
Being in God's image, being his representatives in the created world, his vice regents over the created world, are calling as humanity is to grow our number and expand our borders.

23:34.713 --> 23:38.898
Or you would say, bring new humans into the world and raise them up

23:40.098 --> 23:46.086
and venture out into new territory and bring order to the uncultivated raw wilderness.

23:48.670 --> 23:51.554
Don't expand your borders to take the borders of other countries.

23:52.776 --> 23:53.757
It should probably be said.

23:56.581 --> 24:08.978
But expand the civilization to cultivate and do so consciously and carefully, preserving natural beauty and making it accessible for human flourishing.

24:11.074 --> 24:16.202
As humans increase and spread out across the earth, we learn to work together.

24:16.623 --> 24:22.211
We should, sometimes we do, hopefully we do, so that we can be more fruitful in this cultural mandate.

24:23.774 --> 24:30.544
And as we do that, we find specific abilities that we begin to talk about as our particular calling.

24:33.549 --> 24:39.538
And if you want to know about what your calling is, sometimes people sense a desire to do something

24:39.810 --> 24:42.593
And then very quickly they cut corners and say, I'm called to this.

24:42.673 --> 24:44.035
I had a desire to do this.

24:44.115 --> 24:44.996
And now I'm called to this.

24:46.718 --> 24:47.079
Hold on.

24:47.339 --> 24:48.040
Just wait a minute.

24:48.060 --> 24:48.741
That's a part of it.

24:48.961 --> 24:53.066
Your desire, your aspiration, your holy desire is a part.

24:53.086 --> 24:53.626
That's a piece.

24:54.547 --> 24:55.669
It's one of three pieces.

24:56.750 --> 24:58.893
Also, you need some ability in that thing.

24:59.633 --> 25:00.895
Doesn't matter if you really want to do it.

25:00.915 --> 25:01.656
You're terrible at it.

25:02.016 --> 25:02.777
We don't need you to do it.

25:04.079 --> 25:04.860
You need some ability.

25:05.480 --> 25:06.962
Maybe some God-given ability.

25:07.842 --> 25:09.865
often some cultivated ability.

25:10.365 --> 25:15.973
Sometimes Christians can just talk about giftedness as if it just falls from heaven.

25:16.053 --> 25:16.934
I'm giftedness.

25:17.455 --> 25:19.778
Take an inventory and your spiritual gifts, find out what they are.

25:19.818 --> 25:26.608
Most of them are cultivated, not just received from heaven in a moment.

25:27.369 --> 25:37.202
So aspiration of a heart, abilities, and third is a real life opportunity to help people in need where somebody says to you, hey, we'll give you a job to do this.

25:37.314 --> 25:37.815
Would you do this?

25:37.835 --> 25:40.699
We'll pay you and you go, Oh, I got a calling.

25:41.360 --> 25:41.961
I want to do it.

25:42.442 --> 25:44.705
I'm able to do it and somebody needs me to do it.

25:44.745 --> 25:45.807
I'm meeting a real need.

25:45.827 --> 25:47.389
This is a real opportunity in the world.

25:47.729 --> 25:51.014
That's a calling when those three pieces come together.

25:53.137 --> 26:00.989
So a charge for us this morning from Psalm eight is be good at your God given callings.

26:02.191 --> 26:03.232
God set up the world this way.

26:03.252 --> 26:04.434
It's his cultural mandate.

26:06.242 --> 26:08.005
Trace your calling in life.

26:08.045 --> 26:11.430
Whatever that occupation is, that job, that role, mother, father, that's part of it.

26:12.652 --> 26:17.098
Trace it back to Genesis 1 through Psalm 8 under the providence of God.

26:18.701 --> 26:24.409
Your work this week, tomorrow, Wednesday, Friday, it matters.

26:24.610 --> 26:25.571
Your work matters.

26:27.554 --> 26:35.346
Don't just work for a paycheck, but work with divine purpose as one who knows the God.

26:35.650 --> 26:38.834
who made the world and gave us Psalm 8.

26:39.254 --> 26:43.259
See God's sovereign significance in your work.

26:45.401 --> 26:50.707
And we said that this Psalm has in it an energizing hope for the future.

26:52.069 --> 27:03.922
As Christians, being called and having dominion doesn't stop at the cultural mandate, it brings us to what we call the Great Commission.

27:05.986 --> 27:11.412
where there's far more uncultivated territory to expand into.

27:13.514 --> 27:33.576
I really believe that a healthy church will be both locally engaged in excellence in our vocations and globally mindful, globally prayerful, and sending people to the neediest places around the world.

27:34.277 --> 27:35.378
I know you might feel

27:35.522 --> 27:37.684
Sweden is one of the neediest places.

27:38.865 --> 27:40.007
Send missionaries here.

27:40.267 --> 27:42.830
We don't need to dream and pray and think about the nations.

27:44.691 --> 27:48.075
And if you do it that way, you're not becoming a fully healthy church.

27:51.619 --> 28:02.610
It's a glorious thing as God begins to move among Swedish Christians and send missionaries to the nations, not just from countries that have

28:02.882 --> 28:05.966
10% or 20% or 30% evangelicals.

28:07.368 --> 28:11.534
But may God raise up missionaries from Sweden.

28:12.636 --> 28:17.803
The church in Sweden will be more healthy if it's raising up and sending missionaries.

28:19.586 --> 28:22.430
And maybe some are in this room this morning.

28:26.756 --> 28:27.857
So we're called people.

28:28.639 --> 28:31.122
Third, be a candid people.

28:32.354 --> 28:34.978
This is verse four, verse two.

28:36.380 --> 28:41.087
By candid, I mean honest, real, straightforward.

28:42.870 --> 28:52.183
And in Psalm eight, that means honest about weakness, honest about smallness, honest about sin.

28:52.224 --> 28:56.249
Another way to say it is humble.

28:57.972 --> 28:59.314
Be a humble church.

29:01.186 --> 29:03.388
And it's been so encouraging to see this weekend.

29:04.209 --> 29:11.617
There is a spirit of humility in the church that I wish was more widespread in the American church.

29:13.499 --> 29:17.544
Be humble, like David's astounded question in verse four.

29:18.825 --> 29:30.738
So remember, he's marveling at God's majesty, his heavens, his moon, his stars, and then he says, in light of that, in light of the magisties of the world, the point to the greater majesty of God, he says,

29:30.882 --> 29:33.885
What is man that you're mindful of Him?

29:34.285 --> 29:36.127
Or the son of man that you care for Him?

29:38.589 --> 29:41.372
The answer to David's question is not, man's great.

29:43.674 --> 29:44.555
Lift your head up, David.

29:45.856 --> 29:46.357
Man's great.

29:46.917 --> 29:47.638
That's not the answer.

29:49.080 --> 29:51.142
The answer is, God is great.

29:53.364 --> 29:56.206
And God in His greatness is gracious.

29:57.648 --> 29:59.890
God's great and man is grace.

30:00.930 --> 30:09.538
Grace for man, divine favor, kindness, compassion, gentleness for man is the point of Psalm 8.

30:10.860 --> 30:15.744
Man is the undeserved recipient of God's kindness.

30:17.286 --> 30:18.687
God is strong.

30:18.907 --> 30:20.529
He is infinitely strong.

30:20.909 --> 30:29.938
That means he does not need to gather up strong people, strong churches to fill in gaps in his strength,

30:31.202 --> 30:46.218
Rather, he is so strong that he gathers up the weak so he can show you how strong he is when he defeats seemingly strong foes through weak people.

30:49.021 --> 30:51.544
You know how weak a leader is when they pretend to be strong?

30:51.604 --> 30:53.947
Then they got to flank all their weakness with all the strength?

30:54.427 --> 30:56.209
Our God is not like that.

30:56.229 --> 31:00.594
He is so infinitely strong that he takes babies

31:00.994 --> 31:07.981
and infants and weak churches and shows himself strong.

31:11.143 --> 31:22.034
Verse 2, out of the mouth of babies and infants, you have established strength because of your foes to still the enemy and the avenger.

31:26.498 --> 31:30.962
It's a glorious thing that God helps to weak because we are that.

31:31.682 --> 31:33.464
We are the weak.

31:33.484 --> 31:42.753
So be candid, be honest about weakness, embrace it, embrace smallness, embrace weakness, confess it, cry for help.

31:43.894 --> 31:46.036
Because God loves to hear cries for help.

31:49.399 --> 31:50.901
It reminds me of King Asa.

31:52.002 --> 31:54.004
This is 2 Chronicles chapter 16.

31:55.205 --> 31:57.687
King Asa started well.

31:58.848 --> 32:00.530
And in the 10th year of his reign,

32:02.274 --> 32:03.495
Egypt, no.

32:03.776 --> 32:08.501
Ethiopia came up against him and he felt his weakness.

32:08.762 --> 32:09.843
He felt his neediness.

32:10.043 --> 32:11.625
He cried out for God.

32:11.705 --> 32:13.187
He relied on God.

32:13.327 --> 32:19.875
He leaned on God and God rescued him from Ethiopia against this strong foe.

32:21.236 --> 32:25.061
And then 25 years later, Asa is stronger.

32:27.443 --> 32:28.404
And another foe comes.

32:28.705 --> 32:29.746
This time it's Syria.

32:31.266 --> 32:35.553
And instead of leaning on God, Asa doesn't feel desperate.

32:36.254 --> 32:37.376
He doesn't feel small.

32:37.396 --> 32:38.217
It didn't feel weak.

32:38.738 --> 32:39.980
So he makes arrangement.

32:40.020 --> 32:41.362
He's got international connections.

32:41.402 --> 32:45.769
Now he makes arrangements to get help against Syria.

32:47.933 --> 32:54.583
And the prophet comes to him and tells him of his great folly and mistake.

32:55.084 --> 32:57.228
And then the prophet ends with these wonderful words.

32:57.368 --> 32:58.770
The prophet's name is Hanani.

33:00.290 --> 33:09.102
He ends with these amazing words in verse nine of why you should not lean on your own understanding, your own connections, your own strength.

33:09.442 --> 33:24.302
Why resting God, verse nine, the eyes of the Lord run to and fro throughout the whole earth, not just Israel, the whole earth to give strong support to those whose heart is blameless toward him.

33:26.505 --> 33:30.130
Swedish brothers and sisters, the eyes of King Jesus.

33:31.042 --> 33:31.543
Rome.

33:31.603 --> 33:49.261
They look with energy, with attention throughout the whole earth, including Sweden, to look for candid people who would say, hey, we're weak.

33:50.062 --> 33:50.603
We're small.

33:52.044 --> 33:52.785
Would you help us?

33:53.946 --> 33:57.650
Would you show yourself strong through our weakness?

34:00.610 --> 34:03.893
We're not going to pretend to be strong.

34:03.913 --> 34:05.775
You dare not play big.

34:05.795 --> 34:10.279
You dare not pretend with a God like this who helps the weak.

34:12.581 --> 34:16.024
In doing so, he turns our calculus for strength upside down.

34:17.246 --> 34:18.507
We begin to embrace weakness.

34:19.087 --> 34:20.869
We rejoice in suffering.

34:21.329 --> 34:23.832
We don't despise the day of small things.

34:24.512 --> 34:30.578
We cherish God's strength, God's glory, His majesty, on display in human weakness.

34:31.042 --> 34:33.405
in disability, in suffering.

34:34.967 --> 34:36.529
This is what's at the heart of Psalm 8.

34:37.090 --> 34:46.863
So we said that Psalm 8 was about God's majesty and that there were two modes of His majesty, natural majesty, which any unbeliever can see in a beautiful landscape.

34:47.724 --> 34:58.578
This is about what you'd call peculiar majesty or special majesty, unexpected majesty.

34:59.490 --> 35:09.364
He's not just majestic over the heavens, but He is all the more majestic in defeating strong foes through weak people.

35:10.806 --> 35:13.130
That's where the majesty of God really shines.

35:16.294 --> 35:17.856
So, sweet is church.

35:20.600 --> 35:27.410
You may not only feel small and weak, but feel various waves of opposition

35:29.218 --> 35:41.311
There are foes plural in Psalm 8, verse 2, and there's a singular enemy and a vendor behind those foes.

35:43.893 --> 35:47.517
And so the church is often threatened and embattled and that leads to number 4.

35:49.499 --> 35:51.061
Be a conquering people.

35:52.122 --> 35:52.963
This is verse 8.

35:54.124 --> 35:55.826
This is the strangest part of the Psalm.

35:57.186 --> 35:57.707
I love this.

35:57.767 --> 35:58.808
See if you can track with me.

35:59.388 --> 36:02.472
I know English is more difficult for some than others.

36:02.932 --> 36:04.434
This is probably the hardest part right here.

36:05.075 --> 36:05.836
The end of verse eight.

36:07.157 --> 36:08.799
See if you can track with me.

36:09.760 --> 36:16.127
And last part of verse eight says, whatever passes along the paths of the seas.

36:19.331 --> 36:20.172
What is that?

36:21.774 --> 36:22.915
Why this extra line?

36:23.115 --> 36:23.996
He already said fish.

36:24.897 --> 36:25.778
Like, close the loop.

36:26.786 --> 36:31.112
beasts and birds and fish move on to the next verse.

36:34.035 --> 36:36.359
And fish right here is plural.

36:38.261 --> 36:44.289
And then something singular is lurking at the bottom of verse eight.

36:47.894 --> 36:54.322
Maybe Swedes get this better as a seafaring people than other nations do.

36:55.074 --> 37:03.322
Can you imagine how scary it was to go out on the open sea before we pretended like we knew what was down there?

37:06.605 --> 37:19.498
I mean, nowadays, we're not nearly as fearful as we should be, because we pretend with our science and our modern knowledge, and we personally don't know anything, but like, oh yeah, there's people out there somewhere at university somewhere.

37:19.558 --> 37:21.860
There are people who know us down here, and we're totally safe.

37:22.421 --> 37:23.602
Can you imagine

37:24.034 --> 37:29.641
3,000 years ago as they went out on the Mediterranean and some massive sea creature came up.

37:32.025 --> 37:32.846
I'm just scared to death.

37:33.427 --> 37:35.850
That's very different than a fish.

37:35.870 --> 37:36.671
I don't know what that was.

37:36.691 --> 37:40.456
I don't know how many different species qualified for these scary things.

37:41.417 --> 37:54.034
Elsewhere in the Psalms, in the book of Job two times, Psalm 74, Psalm 104, the book of Job, Isaiah 27, verse one, we hear about a creature called Leviathan.

37:56.610 --> 38:02.719
Leviathan says Isaiah is the fleeing, twisting serpent, the dragon that is in the sea.

38:03.601 --> 38:06.004
Now remember, psalmate is poetry.

38:07.527 --> 38:08.869
This is an image.

38:09.670 --> 38:13.516
And Genesis 1 did talk about God making the great sea creatures.

38:13.656 --> 38:16.420
We tend to blow over this pretty quick in the modern world.

38:18.804 --> 38:20.126
We still have this fascination.

38:20.887 --> 38:25.554
In the United States, I don't know how global it is, the end of July is shark week.

38:27.010 --> 38:35.420
I don't know if it's National Geographic, one of the channels, and they just show shark shows and documentaries all week.

38:35.440 --> 38:40.986
And there is something ancient in the human soul that is fearful about the shark.

38:42.688 --> 38:43.549
And Megalodon.

38:46.012 --> 38:46.692
Oh my goodness.

38:46.913 --> 38:48.795
Listen to this podcast about Megalodon.

38:50.276 --> 38:51.818
And at the end, it's fascinating.

38:52.999 --> 38:55.282
They're asking this expert about Megalodon.

38:55.810 --> 38:59.213
Did Megalodon have any foes, any natural predators?

38:59.494 --> 39:02.056
Well, I mean, yeah, pretty much ate everything.

39:02.116 --> 39:07.841
However, there was this ancient creature that some call Leviathan.

39:07.861 --> 39:10.944
And Megalodon and Leviathan would eat each other's young.

39:11.004 --> 39:14.127
That's the only natural foe of Megalodon.

39:14.227 --> 39:17.571
Who knows what Leviathan stood for in the ancient world?

39:18.011 --> 39:21.895
And included all sorts of shark, big shark, whales, whatever.

39:22.215 --> 39:23.256
This is Hebrew poetry.

39:23.897 --> 39:25.298
This is a song of David.

39:25.538 --> 39:29.684
Songs draw on imagery and don't speak with the precision of epistles.

39:31.166 --> 39:39.977
But even though this line may not be clear exactly what is in David's mind, I think the implications for us in 2025 are plenty clear.

39:42.541 --> 39:55.538
If it hints at Leviathan as the epitome and metaphorical embodiment of evil, then our call today relates to sin and to evil.

39:56.226 --> 39:58.388
That's what Leviathan's embodying, poetically.

40:00.270 --> 40:02.352
This is the call for you.

40:03.793 --> 40:06.135
Defeat sin.

40:06.155 --> 40:07.176
Defeat your sin first.

40:08.157 --> 40:08.798
Tread on it.

40:09.779 --> 40:11.100
Put your feet on it.

40:11.320 --> 40:14.763
Don't give the serpent leash in your garden.

40:18.367 --> 40:19.608
What is that for you right now?

40:19.748 --> 40:26.034
When I hear, when you hear a preacher say, don't let sin run free in your life.

40:26.626 --> 40:27.507
What's the sin?

40:27.527 --> 40:32.975
It might seem intractable.

40:33.055 --> 40:34.977
I've struggled with the sin for so long.

40:34.997 --> 40:36.019
I'll never get over this thing.

40:36.499 --> 40:45.812
Psalm 8 says to you, with the help of the Holy Spirit, the help of Christian brothers and sisters, you can put Leviathan under your feet.

40:47.234 --> 40:56.146
Whatever passes along the path of the sea, let it be called this morning to be a conquering people over our own sin.

40:57.954 --> 41:06.084
And now we come to this point in the Psalm, as we get ready to close, and we're missing the most important piece.

41:09.688 --> 41:12.612
As it stands, Psalm 8 is stuck.

41:14.394 --> 41:24.246
We're supposed to be a commending people, a called people, a candid people, a conquering people, and there's a glaring problem that that idea of conquering brought up.

41:25.908 --> 41:27.570
This is how Hebrews 2 8

41:28.898 --> 41:29.999
summarizes the problem.

41:30.219 --> 41:33.823
Now we're jumping a new testament in Psalm 8's interview.

41:34.343 --> 41:42.331
Hebrews is reading Psalm 8 and he's talking to us as a Christian and as Christians.

41:42.351 --> 41:48.596
He comments very simply reading Psalm 8, we do not yet see everything in subjection to man.

41:51.719 --> 41:58.866
So Psalm 8 is echoing Genesis 1, but something terrible has gone wrong in the world.

41:58.946 --> 42:01.829
between Genesis 1 and Psalm 8.

42:07.335 --> 42:07.795
Our sin.

42:10.518 --> 42:14.001
Something is not yet complete when David writes Psalm 8.

42:15.283 --> 42:20.888
God in his peculiar majesty has given humble man dominion over the works of his hands.

42:21.369 --> 42:24.272
But Hebrews says, we're not seeing that yet.

42:25.273 --> 42:26.354
That's not completed yet.

42:27.906 --> 42:28.847
And what's the solution?

42:28.867 --> 42:32.091
In the next verse in Hebrews, Hebrews 2, 9.

42:34.053 --> 42:51.772
But we see Him who for a little while was made lower than the angels, namely Jesus, crowned with glory and honor because of the suffering of His death so that by the grace of God He might taste death for everyone.

42:52.733 --> 42:57.298
So the vision of Psalm 8 is locked up from its completion.

42:57.410 --> 43:00.935
in human sin until Jesus opens it.

43:02.237 --> 43:12.854
So we end here with Jesus as the hinge that brings the majesty of Psalm 8 into the weakness and into the hope of our lives.

43:13.935 --> 43:17.421
So my fifth and final charge to you is actually a promise.

43:18.162 --> 43:20.966
And that's sweet to end with a promise and another charge.

43:22.148 --> 43:26.194
Number five, it's a promise in Christ.

43:26.306 --> 43:29.270
will be a crowned people.

43:31.452 --> 43:33.835
You will be a crowned people.

43:34.856 --> 43:47.412
And as verse five, crowned means you will be honored with final, unending, unchanging honor, honor that only grows and sweetens forever.

43:48.593 --> 43:55.762
So after David asked in verse four, what's man that you're mindful of him, the son of man that you care for him, he says in verse five,

43:55.938 --> 44:03.187
yet you have made him a little lower than the heavenly beings and crowned him with glory and honor.

44:04.188 --> 44:24.914
And for Christians, the answer to the ancient riddle of Psalm 8 is that Christ has come and fulfilled the destiny of humanity by going to the cross for us, by rising again to new life, ascending to heaven, and being seated at the right hand

44:25.346 --> 44:27.808
of the majesty on high.

44:29.410 --> 44:37.297
So now Jesus as man, the God man, is crowned with glory and honor.

44:37.938 --> 44:44.184
And Jesus is crowned on heaven's throne right now, August 10th, 2025.

44:44.644 --> 44:45.926
He is on heaven's throne.

44:48.688 --> 44:54.674
And he's building his church, including in Sweden on heaven's throne.

44:55.010 --> 45:06.725
And he's beautifying his church and his church with her groom will one day rise with him and ascend to the throne and will be crowned with glory and honor.

45:06.765 --> 45:12.533
And so we, his church, are Christ-adoring people.

45:13.955 --> 45:17.479
We commend him and we commend each other.

45:18.080 --> 45:22.706
We're called to our local vocations and we're commissioned into a global cause.

45:23.714 --> 45:27.600
We are candid about our smallness and our weakness and our sin and our need.

45:28.481 --> 45:32.747
We seek to fight back and conquer sin and evil, beginning with our own hearts first.

45:34.109 --> 45:51.954
And we know that just as surely as Christ has been crowned and sits crowned right now in heaven, so we too, His people will be crowned and enjoy Him as our great reward forever.

45:53.218 --> 46:01.390
We will adore His majesty and be luminaries of divine majesty in the name of Jesus.

46:02.872 --> 46:03.613
Let's pray together.

46:04.875 --> 46:13.648
So Father in Heaven, thank you for the sweet fellowship this weekend with these dear brothers and sisters in Sweden.

46:14.610 --> 46:22.962
And I know other Nordens as well, but particularly these dear Swedish brothers and sisters.

46:24.482 --> 46:36.215
Father, it is so sweet to hear of your inspired vision for your church and to resonate together as those who love Jesus and adore Him that He is on His throne.

46:36.255 --> 46:38.137
He knows exactly what He's doing.

46:38.558 --> 46:48.909
He has all authority in heaven and on earth, and He is working His plans and showing His power in His perfect timing among every tribe and tongue in nation.

46:50.371 --> 46:53.394
We adore the majesty of your Son.

46:53.922 --> 46:55.141
And pray now in His name.

46:56.380 --> 46:56.786
Amen.

